=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

Operator Overloading is a compile-time polymorphism feature that allows
existing operators to work with user-defined types. It improves code
readability by making objects behave like built-in types. Operators are
implemented using operator functions and can be member or non-member
functions. Commonly overloaded operators include +, <<, >>, =, [], (),
++, and ==.

